4k damage?!  /gasp <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uoobydewby.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Oobydewby</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/18/01 1:56:30 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> WOW</span><hr size=1> hey, don't stone me for this, but who is taking bets on how long it will take verant to nerf this? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=maruku14>Maruku14</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/18/01 3:11:18 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Don't get overexcited</span><hr size=1> I can understand why people are getting excited over this skill, but I would prefer people didn't go overboard with their enthusiasm (and make Verant wonder if they gave Wizards something excessively good), so I'm going to put things into proper perspective.<br>
<br>
With Spell Casting Fury at level three, which demands the effective equivalent of completing level 59 four times, Wizards, and of course other casters, will achieve a critical nuke for double the typical amount, seven percent of the time.  This equates to a seven percent increase in their overall damage output.<br>
<br>
This doesn't mean, as one series of screenshots seemed to be illustrating, that we can expect to see criticals popping up every third nuke.  Try every 14th.  It's a damage improvement - a very minor one - that we have no control over.  Those lucky strings of criticals must, by definition, be interspaced with elongated streaks of bad luck.<br>
<br>
So what does a seven percent increase in damage mean, in the grand scheme of things?  Well, let's hypothesize the typical quadding Wizard, meds for, what, 24 mana per tick?  Probably has Barrier of Force and at least Flowing Thought 1.  So 28 mana per tick.  A little math, ignoring insignificant considerations, puts us at 28 * 1.07 = ~29.9, or let's call it effectively 30 mana regen, which means that having invested in three points of those oh-so-uber critical nukes is about the same as having bought two points of Mental Clarity.<br>
<br>
I recall reading one poster pointing out that with each rain, Wizards can land a critical nuke three times, and with each piller, a breathtaking four criticals are possible.  This reminded me of a Beavis and Butthead episode: the duo were ripped off by a vending machine, which just barely failed to dispense their purchased product, but logic made them conclude that if they were to purchase the same item again, they would get two for the price of one.  Can we all spot the flaw in this logic?  This showcases the idea that critical nukes are less about genuine worth and more about spectacle.  They may be perfectly okay to anyone who hasn't analyzed (or intuited) the reality, but I demand a little more personal improvement in an ability before I start praising it as world-shattering.<br>
<br>
I'm also a little skeptical of the Spell Casting Fury Mastery ability Wizards get.  My guess is it will tack on an extra one percent chance per level, totalling ten percent.  Why do I figure this?  It has to do with the thoroughly unremarkable nature of all the other Wizard-specific abilities.  Wizards get eight of them, fully four of which are one-shot escape abilities or ones which facilitate escape, and a fifth is a one-shot offensive capability of undefined but expectedly dubious value.<br>
<br>
The others?  For a mere three L59s, Wizards can make their flapping, buggy FT4 usable for something other than causing them to suffer pseudo-ressurection effects for no apparent reason.  Or, for _six_ L59s, they can really power up: Sunstrike will no longer take a staggering seven seconds to cast, but rather a remarkably speedy 6.3 seconds.<br>
<br>
Before you say  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=maruku14>Maruku14</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/18/01 3:14:47 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Don't get overexcited</span><hr size=1> (continued; reached apparent text limit)<br>
<br>
Before you say &quot;It's better than nothing&quot;, that's not what I was disputing; I was merely submitting the known effects of Wizards' woefully pathetic repertoir of class-specific abilities as strong evidence for the idea that any upgrade to critical nukes is not likely to be dramatic in the least.<br>
<br>
Two things I want from Verant, concerning critical nukes: 1) Do not nerf them.  Remember, you'd be nerfing more than just Wizards.  2) Is there anything wrong with letting bystanders know how much the critical did?  Meleer classes get to show off.  Simple math proves critical nukes are not a significant damage booster, so their main worth lies in their ooh-aah value.  This is dampened significantly when people have to ask &quot;How much did that do?&quot;<br>
